Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Abdelmadjid Chergui¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay Area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 trips in the dataset with 16 features:

bike_id bike_share_for_all_trip duration_sec end_station_id end_station_latitude end_station_longitude end_station_name end_time member_birth_year member_gender start_station_id start_station_latitude start_station_longitude start_station_name start_time user_type The dataset contain 2 datetime variables (start_time, end_time), 3 categorical variables (user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip) and a variable that contain stations names (start_station_name, end_station_name) which there is 329 station and the rest of variable are numerical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in different patterns and characteristics of trips like duration or trips taken in terms of time of day, day of the week, or month of the year with its variation by user type and gender.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

i'll use all the columns in the dataset except the latitude and longitude columns.

let's first drop the columns that i don't need in my analysis.

In [17]:
def my_count_plot(df, x, hue_var=None, color=0, palette=None, order=None, figsize=(14, 6)):
    """a quick hack to make count plot """
    if figsize:
        plt.figure(figsize=figsize)

    sb.countplot(data=df, x=x, hue=hue_var, color=sb.color_palette()[color], palette=palette, order=order, edgecolor='black')
    x = x.replace('_', " ")
    if hue_var:
        hue_var = hue_var.replace('_', " ")

    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {x} {'by' if hue_var else ''}'''.title(), fontsize=14, weight="bold")
    plt.xlabel(x.title(), fontsize=10, weight="bold")
    plt.ylabel('Frequency'.title(), fontsize=10, weight="bold");

In [24]:
def plot_top_frequencies(df, column, top=10):
    """a quick hack to plot top frequencies by a given column."""
    # set plot dimensions
    plt.figure(figsize=[14, 6])

    df[column] \
        .value_counts(ascending=True) \
        .tail(top) \
        .plot(kind='barh');

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color = default_color)
    plt.ylim([0, 120])

  • customers take longer trips than subscribers on average.
  • trips on weekends take longer than other days trips.
  • trips around 2 to 3 a.m and the between 11 a.m to 3 p.m take longer on average then trips on other times.

taking into account that only 3622 members are in Other category so the result may not be accurate enough.

Looking back on the point plots, it doesn't seem like there's a systematic interaction effect between the three categorical variables.

Conclusions¶

my investigation of Ford GoBike System Data had lead me to the following conclusions:

  • the overwhelming majority of users are subscribers.
  • the average trip duration is between 9 and 15 minutes.
  • most customers are males.
  • most members have between 25 and 35 years old.
  • San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 is the most frequent station taking it into account as a start and as an end station.
  • customers take longer trips than subscribers on average.
  • trips on weekends take longer than weekdays trips.
  • trips around 2 to 3 a.m and the between 11 a.m to 3 p.m take longer on average then trips on other times.
  • members across ages take the same average duration trips with a slight increase in older people.
  • average duration for Customer in weekends increases vary rapidly in comparison to the increase for Subscriber members,

and that also apply for the members who are not enrolled in the bike_share_for_all_trip program in comparison to members who are enrolled.
